# Plot 1 work

dfc_harm <- dfc %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = harm_personally:harm_plants_animals,
    names_to = "question",
    values_to = "harm"
  ) %>% 
  filter(harm != -1)

harm_plotL0 <- dfc_harm %>% 
  group_by(year, question) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(tot = n()) %>% 
  slice(rep(1:n(), each = 5)) %>% 
  select(tot)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'year' (override with `.groups` argument)
## Adding missing grouping variables: `year`
harm_plotR0 <- dfc_harm %>%
  group_by(year, question, harm) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(n = n())
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'year', 'question' (override with `.groups` argument)
harm_plot0 <- cbind(harm_plotL0, harm_plotR0) %>% 
  select(-year...3) %>% 
  mutate(year = year...1,
         perc = (n / tot) * 100) %>% 
  select(year, question, harm, n, tot, perc)
## New names:
## * year -> year...1
## * year -> year...3
dfc_harm <- dfc_harm %>% # making these values look nice for plot
  mutate(question2 = revalue(as.factor(question), 
                             c("harm_dev_countries" = "Developing Countries",
                               "harm_future_gen" = "Future Generations",
                               "harm_personally" = "You Personally",
                               "harm_plants_animals" = "Plants & Animals",
                               "harm_US" = "USA")),
         harm2 = revalue(as.factor(harm), 
                        c("0" = "Don't know",
                          "1" = "Not at all",
                          "2" = "Only a little",
                          "3" = "A moderate amount",
                          "4" = "A great deal")))

harm_plotL <- dfc_harm %>% 
  group_by(yr, question2) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(tot = n()) %>% 
  slice(rep(1:n(), each = 5)) %>% 
  select(tot)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'yr' (override with `.groups` argument)
## Adding missing grouping variables: `yr`
harm_plotR <- dfc_harm %>%
  group_by(yr, question2, harm2) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(n = n())
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'yr', 'question2' (override with `.groups` argument)
harm_plot <- cbind(harm_plotL, harm_plotR) %>% 
  select(year = 1, everything(), -yr...3) %>% 
  mutate(perc = (n / tot) * 100,
         year = ymd(year, truncated = 2L)) %>% 
  select(year, question2, harm2, n, tot, perc) %>% 
  mutate(question2 = factor(question2, # making sure levels are in order I want for when I facet wrap
                            levels = c("You Personally", "Future Generations",
                                       "USA", "Developing Countries",
                                       "Plants & Animals")))
## New names:
## * yr -> yr...1
## * yr -> yr...3
# Plot 2 work

dfc_pol <- dfc %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = reg_CO2_pollutant:reg_coal_emissions,
    names_to = "Policy",
    values_to = "Support"
  ) %>% 
  filter(Support != -1)

dfc_pol <- dfc_pol %>% # making these values look nice for plot
  mutate(Policy = revalue(as.factor(Policy), 
                             c("reg_CO2_pollutant" = "Regulate Carbon Dioxide Emissions",
                               "reg_utilities" = "Regulate Utility Energy Sources",
                               "fund_research" = "Fund Renewable Energy Research",
                               "reg_coal_emissions" = "Regulate Coal Power Plant Emissions")),
         Support = revalue(as.factor(Support), 
                        c("1" = "Strongly oppose",
                          "2" = "Somewhat oppose",
                          "3" = "Somewhat support",
                          "4" = "Strongly support")))

pol_plotL <- dfc_pol %>% 
  group_by(year, Policy) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(totpol = n()) %>% 
  slice(rep(1:n(), each = 4)) %>% 
  select(totpol)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'year' (override with `.groups` argument)
## Adding missing grouping variables: `year`
pol_plotR <- dfc_pol %>%
  group_by(year, Policy, Support) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(npol = n())
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'year', 'Policy' (override with `.groups` argument)
pol_plot <- cbind(pol_plotL, pol_plotR) %>% 
  select(-year...3) %>% 
  mutate(year = year...1,
         percpol = (npol / totpol) * 100) %>% 
  select(year, Policy, Support, npol, totpol, percpol)
## New names:
## * year -> year...1
## * year -> year...3

Data Source

Data Source

These figures utilize data from the Climate Change in the American Mind (CCAM) project. Led by the Yale Program on Climate Change Communication and the George Mason Center for Climate Change Communication, CCAM consists of national survey data on climate change beliefs collected between 2008 and 2018 (excluding 2009) and includes over 20,000 data points.

Raleigh Goodwin created the plots on this page using the ggplot package.

Citations:

Yale Program on Climate Change Communication (YPCCC) & George Mason University Center for Climate Change Communication (Mason 4C). (2020). Climate Change in the American Mind: National survey data on public opinion (2008-2018) [Data file and codebook]. doi: 10.17605/OSF.IO/JW79P

Ballew, M. T., Leiserowitz, A., Roser-Renouf, C., Rosenthal, S. A., Kotcher, J. E., Marlon, J. R., Lyon, E., Goldberg, M. H., & Maibach, E. W. (2019). Climate Change in the American Mind: Data, tools, and trends. Environment: Science and Policy for Sustainable Development, 61(3), 4-18. doi: 10.1080/00139157.2019.1589300

dfc_voter %>% 
  dplyr::group_by(party_w_leaners, registered_voter) %>% 
  dplyr::summarize(mean_worry = mean(worry),
                   n = n(),
                   se = (sd(worry)/sqrt(n))) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = party_w_leaners, mean_worry, fill = as.factor(registered_voter))) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge",
           alpha = .85) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_worry - se, ymax = mean_worry + se),
                width = .2,
                position = position_dodge(.9),
                color = "darkgray") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "plasma",
                       name = "Registered Voter",
                       labels = c("Yes", "No", "Don't know")) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("Republican", "Democrat", "Independent/\nOther", "No party/\nApolitical")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = c("Not at all worried", "Not very worried", "Somewhat worried", "Very worried"),
                     breaks = 1:4, limits = c(0, 4)) +
  labs(y = "Average Worry", x = "Political Leanings",
       title = '"How worried are you about global warming?"') +
  theme_light() +
  theme(plot.title.position = "plot",
        legend.position = "top")
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'party_w_leaners' (override with `.groups` argument)
